==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Possibly an {{liushu|2|nocap=yes}} of a person kneeling ({{zh-l|*卩}}), and a small stroke to accentuate the knee (now {{zh-l|*厂}}).<ref>季旭昇，2002《說文新證.下冊》，台北：藝文印書館，2002年10月第1版。p.72</ref> Not cognate with {{zh-l|戹}} (“yoke”) but eventually they shared meanings. 

{{w|Shuowen Jiezi}} interprets it as {{Han compound|厂|卪|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s|t2=joint; node|nocap=yes}} – {{w|Wood#Knots|wood knot}}.

<references/>

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=戹,阨,𠂬,𭠀}}
Probably related to {{och-l|嗌|throat}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Or borrowed from {{bor|och|txb|räk-}} and {{bor|och|xto|räk-|t=to stretch, to spread}}.<ref>{{cite-book|1=en|year=1998|author={{w|Alexander Lubotsky}}|title=The Bronze Age and Early Iron Age peoples of Eastern Central Asia|chapter=Tocharian Loan Words in Old Chinese: Chariots, Chariot Gear, and Town Building|chapterurl=https://scholarlypublications.universiteitleiden.nl/access/item%3A2883003/view|pages=379-390}}</ref>

